WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.720
Hi everybody, welcome to the Data Science Hangout. If you're joining for the first time,

00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:17.799
I'm Rachel. It's great to meet you. I'm calling in from Nashville today, so I have a different

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:23.920
background behind me. If this is your first Hangout, this is an open space for the whole

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:29.600
data science community to connect and chat about data science leadership, questions you're

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:35.240
facing, and what's going on in the world of data science. So we want this to be a space

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:39.860
where everybody can participate and we can hear from everyone. So there's three ways

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:45.959
that you can ask questions. You can jump in live, and raising your hand on Zoom works

00:00:45.959 --> 00:00:51.439
well for this. You could put questions in the Zoom chat. Just put a little star next

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:56.080
to your question if you want me to read it, or else I'll just call on you to jump in the

00:00:56.080 --> 00:01:00.919
conversation too. And then we also have a Slido link that Tyler will share in just

00:01:00.919 --> 00:01:07.160
a second, where you can ask questions anonymously too. Just want to reiterate, we love to hear

00:01:07.160 --> 00:01:13.040
from everyone, no matter your level of experience or area of work. And with all that, I'm so

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:19.519
happy to be joined by my co-host for today, Daren Eiri. Daren is Director of Data Science

00:01:19.519 --> 00:01:25.400
at Arrowhead General Insurance Agency. And Daren, I'd love to kick things off with having

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:29.199
you introduce yourself and maybe share a bit about your role and the work that you

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:30.199
do.

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:35.599
Sure. So thanks for having me today. So I lead the data science team at Arrowhead General

00:01:35.599 --> 00:01:45.400
Insurance. Arrowhead is one of several subsidiaries within our parent organization, Brown and

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:51.620
Brown Insurance. And we're kind of set up as like a shared service within the organization.

00:01:51.620 --> 00:02:01.279
So we're very decentralized, and not every subsidiary within Brown and Brown has their

00:02:01.279 --> 00:02:08.940
own data science team looking at data. Sometimes they haven't even looked at their data, right?

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:15.820
So our team is there to provide support for those types of needs. It's not always something

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:20.580
where we're building a predictive model. Most of the time, it's just trying to find value

00:02:20.580 --> 00:02:29.220
in the data that they already have and what their data is, what the data actually looks

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:37.380
like. So sometimes we'll try to find business value in that data, whether it's trying to

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:44.259
improve their underwriting functions. Sometimes we'll try to look for ways to price insurance

00:02:44.259 --> 00:02:53.100
products. But in other cases, sometimes it's just looking at the data and trying to understand

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:59.059
how to affect the bottom line. So that's kind of high level.

00:02:59.059 --> 00:03:03.300
That's great. How does that engagement usually work? Or how do you get in touch with the

00:03:03.300 --> 00:03:05.419
teams or work together with them?

00:03:05.419 --> 00:03:14.259
Yeah, so everything is budgeted, of course. So when we are planning for our budget for

00:03:14.259 --> 00:03:22.539
next year, which usually is late summer, we make an email list of anyone who's interested

00:03:22.539 --> 00:03:30.259
in doing things related to data science and analytics. And we have kind of like a menu,

00:03:30.259 --> 00:03:34.820
so to speak, of like, here's what we've done, and here's what we're capable of. Are these

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:41.339
things that you're interested in doing? And so that will get sent out to the other subsidiaries

00:03:41.339 --> 00:03:45.740
within our organization, and they'll reach out to us. And then we'll have initial calls

00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:51.500
with them and try to understand what their actual problem is.

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:58.100
Sometimes it's, they jump straight to, I want to have a machine learning model. I want deep

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:05.419
learning to do something cool, right? And that's not always the case. Sometimes you

00:04:05.419 --> 00:04:10.779
just start off simple, just looking at the data itself and trying to understand what

00:04:10.779 --> 00:04:18.500
the problem is and building a solution for that problem versus building that shiny object

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:22.820
that they think that they want, but they really don't.

00:04:23.019 --> 00:04:27.019
I imagine that takes some good communication skills, too.

00:04:27.019 --> 00:04:35.299
Yeah, and sometimes it's setting expectations. You always want to be clear, you know, what,

00:04:35.299 --> 00:04:39.100
whatever you're building, what it's going to be capable of doing and what its limitations

00:04:39.100 --> 00:04:46.579
are. I think we're pretty lucky within our organization. Not many people that I work

00:04:46.579 --> 00:04:53.459
with, they all have a pretty good idea of what we're capable of and the limitations.

00:04:53.459 --> 00:04:59.579
And for the most part, they're always pretty invested in the work that we do. So, you know,

00:04:59.579 --> 00:05:06.579
having that stakeholder investment, I think we have a much easier time than other organizations,

00:05:06.579 --> 00:05:09.579
at least from my experience.

00:05:09.579 --> 00:05:13.899
While we wait for questions to come in from everyone here, I'd love to ask you, what is

00:05:13.899 --> 00:05:18.380
something that you're really excited about in data science right now or are thinking

00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:22.540
about the year ahead?

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:27.380
For me personally, I think there is a lot of opportunity within the insurance industry

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:33.220
to make a difference. You have all these insured tech startups trying to, you know, disrupt

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:42.179
the industry, right? We are a much more formal insurance company. So, you know, I think we're

00:05:42.179 --> 00:05:49.820
kind of catching up to using data more efficiently and effectively within the organization. So,

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:55.980
from my perspective, there's a lot of opportunities for the data scientist to build meaningful

00:05:55.980 --> 00:06:02.700
products, you know, whatever that might end up being, whether it's a dashboard or a report

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:09.179
that provides some insights to provide business value, a predictive model, right? We have

00:06:09.179 --> 00:06:14.940
a lot of opportunity to make a difference. Whereas, you know, I think other spaces, you

00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:23.700
know, I think we'll get more competitive. And I think the leadership in our organization

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:29.660
makes it a big priority for us to leverage data and analytics to make sure that we don't

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:33.220
fall behind.

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:38.220
Are you hiring a lot of people right now? Or what does the team look like? How many people

00:06:38.260 --> 00:06:44.500
Yeah, so we're a pretty small team. It's so I mentioned, we're a decentralized organization.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:51.619
So there's other teams within a larger organization that does data analytics, they might be doing

00:06:51.619 --> 00:06:58.619
something different. One team is very focused on on Bayesian statistics, for example, and

00:06:58.619 --> 00:07:03.660
they have a different client focus. Again, our we're kind of like internal consultants.

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:09.459
So we're helping the businesses internally. There are some other teams that are focused

00:07:09.459 --> 00:07:22.739
on helping the business with customers externally. So sorry, I kind of drifted off. What was

00:07:22.739 --> 00:07:23.739
the original question?

00:07:23.739 --> 00:07:28.140
No, just as you were talking about the work that the team does, and the big opportunity

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:32.739
to make a difference. I was curious if you were hiring across the team.

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:37.380
Yeah, so we're a pretty small organization, or small team. We have right now two other

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:49.339
data scientists on the team. And then we are looking at hiring another data analyst. And

00:07:49.339 --> 00:07:54.420
we have an intern starting in the summer as well. So we're hoping to have that person

00:07:54.420 --> 00:08:01.980
grow within our team and that position hopefully would end up becoming a full time position

00:08:02.019 --> 00:08:06.420
with our team. So hopefully by the end of this year, we'll have four other people.

00:08:06.899 --> 00:08:12.619
Awesome. I see there's a few questions coming in on from the chat. Andreas, would you want

00:08:12.619 --> 00:08:14.019
to jump in and ask that question?

00:08:15.059 --> 00:08:19.540
Sure. I'm always interested in someone who has a title that looks like they're a bit

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:24.779
managerial. How much of it is managerial? How much can you still do hands on technical

00:08:24.779 --> 00:08:29.299
stuff? And is it something you can decide for yourself? Or is it sort of dictated to

00:08:29.299 --> 00:08:29.619
you?

00:08:30.019 --> 00:08:38.020
Mm hmm. Yeah, that's always, I think, a hard thing to balance when you're at a position

00:08:38.020 --> 00:08:43.340
where you're managing a team, and you're in a technical space. I think other people have

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:51.700
mentioned that you don't want to lose that technical skill set if you can. I don't do

00:08:51.739 --> 00:08:58.659
the day to day, like modeling or analytics and looking at the data specifically. That's

00:08:58.659 --> 00:09:06.099
kind of what the rest of the team does. So a lot of my time is spent kind of like doing

00:09:06.099 --> 00:09:13.460
project management, product ownership, you know, trying to, you know, remove any road

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:19.059
blocks, and working with the stakeholders to make sure that, you know, we have a, you

00:09:19.059 --> 00:09:24.619
know, a path forward. Because that sometimes can happen where, you know, priorities

00:09:24.619 --> 00:09:32.940
change, and then the business has a different priority, they want to switch projects. But I

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:37.340
don't know, it's, it's, it's kind of difficult. I was talking to a friend of mine about this

00:09:37.340 --> 00:09:46.059
yesterday, and he's spending 50% managing and 50%, you know, doing technical work. And

00:09:48.179 --> 00:09:53.700
at that point, he doesn't have time to work on the projects and have that project management

00:09:53.700 --> 00:09:58.940
hat on. And, you know, move things forward, because he's still involved in the technical

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:05.700
side of things. So I think you do kind of let go of that technical role, so to speak. So my

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:10.460
time, if it is technical, it's kind of like making things a bit more efficient, or making

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:16.179
sure that our APIs are that we have, because that's how we service our models are running

00:10:16.739 --> 00:10:22.380
efficiently. I kind of have a unique perspective, because I have an IT background. So I

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:30.940
used to like systems administration. So we use, you know, RStudio products. So we have

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:36.299
RStudio Workbench, we have RStudio Connect, and then Package Manager. So I manage all that

00:10:36.299 --> 00:10:43.820
infrastructure, and the servers that host those products. So making sure that that kind of

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:50.700
stays available. And, you know, I think one of our goals for our team is making sure that

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:58.260
those APIs that we have released as production, that they stay operating during business

00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:03.500
hours. So that's kind of a challenge that I have to kind of balance. And sometimes that ends up

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:08.059
with me, you know, working more than I should, I think, and especially during off hours when I

00:11:08.059 --> 00:11:14.659
have to do like, you know, the IT maintenance stuff. But it's a need that I think that our team

00:11:14.659 --> 00:11:19.099
has to have. And I think that's also one of the things that gets kind of brought up is, you

00:11:19.099 --> 00:11:25.979
know, how do you work with IT as a data science team, and I kind of take that responsibility so

00:11:25.979 --> 00:11:33.500
that we don't have to rely so heavily on an IT team to do what we need to do technically. So it

00:11:33.539 --> 00:11:41.260
makes us more agile to make things work the way we want it to work. Yeah, that's I kind of went

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:48.140
off on a tangent there. But in short, I don't do a lot of coding as much as I'd like to. When I

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:53.659
do, it's kind of just making little tools here and there to make us more efficient as a team, and

00:11:53.659 --> 00:12:00.380
to monitor things. But the actual like data analytics, building models, I haven't been

00:12:00.380 --> 00:12:01.500
doing that as much.

00:12:04.979 --> 00:12:10.820
That's interesting that you say you wear two hats, obviously, or many hats, but are doing the

00:12:10.820 --> 00:12:18.659
IT administration as well. Is there a point where you think that would get handed over to IT?

00:12:19.659 --> 00:12:25.700
Um, I mean, I think that would always be nice. And, you know, I think, fortunately, we have a

00:12:25.700 --> 00:12:32.739
close relationship with the people in IT to make, you know, significant changes if we need to, but

00:12:32.739 --> 00:12:41.179
once it's kind of in place, then there's not much else that needs to be done. The things that, you

00:12:41.179 --> 00:12:47.900
know, that I can handle are, you know, just day to day things that are really small and doesn't

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:52.659
require a lot of effort. So once everything's working in place, and it's not too much of a

00:12:52.659 --> 00:12:57.859
responsibility, but if something isn't working, then of course, that's kind of when you know,

00:12:57.859 --> 00:13:02.780
everything is put off to the side. And that's when you have to work with IT to understand like what

00:13:02.780 --> 00:13:12.020
the problem is, and it's a networking issue. You know, is it something on the, you know, the other

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:18.500
side where the business, the subsidiary, the other company that we're working with, if their calls

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:22.659
aren't coming in correctly, as we were expecting it to, making sure that there's nothing on their

00:13:22.659 --> 00:13:29.539
end that's a problem. Yeah, it's kind of kind of a mixture of problems that you have to deal with.

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:37.380
I see Ishwar, you just put a question to the chat a bit earlier, too. Do you want to jump in and ask

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:37.900
that live?

00:13:38.739 --> 00:13:46.619
Yep, absolutely. Hey, everyone. I'm Ishwar. I'm a data scientist at Nissan here in the supply chain

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:54.780
manufacturing assembly plant, basically in Tennessee. So as you mentioned, in the discussion

00:13:54.780 --> 00:14:03.739
that looking at deep learning, and neural net stuff. So I was just curious if you have, or your

00:14:03.739 --> 00:14:10.539
team has ever experimented or try to work on the deep learning or neural nets, at least if not,

00:14:10.539 --> 00:14:15.500
you know, in the level of computer vision. I understand in the insurance industry, as I'm

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:24.539
working on several projects, but it doesn't much need to train very high capacity, deep learning

00:14:24.539 --> 00:14:32.140
and neural net models. So I was just curious, if you have you see any potential opportunities to

00:14:32.140 --> 00:14:38.380
work on those deep learning models that can be applied in into the insurance industry.

00:14:38.859 --> 00:14:47.900
Being specific, if you have your team has thought about looking at if any deep learning models

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:56.619
can be utilized to make your project or the project you're working on to make it more robust,

00:14:57.659 --> 00:15:04.539
or at least, you know, if it is 98 to make it 99, or near, you know, closer to perfect. So

00:15:05.179 --> 00:15:08.219
just kind of to make the point of discussion.

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:14.700
Yeah, that's, that's always a fun question to think about. Short answer is our team does not

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:21.900
do any deep learning. I think in the insurance industry as a whole, yeah, I think there's

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:30.380
opportunities to yeah, I think, you know, I could be wrong. I'm not sure how other insurance

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:36.940
industries are thinking about it. But you know, there's a lot of investment in that, right? It's,

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:42.940
it's kind of you're going into like an R&D focus versus like, developing a product that

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:47.179
could actually be used. And you know, there's a high likelihood of, you know, the business using

00:15:47.179 --> 00:15:55.900
it. So so there's certain risks involved with building products that leverage deep learning.

00:15:56.539 --> 00:16:00.140
But I think it depends on the application. So

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:13.900
from a very simple perspective, I mean, just being able to read, you know, handwritten documents,

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:18.619
there are scans, there's a lot of scanned documents that are, you know, still being used

00:16:18.619 --> 00:16:23.739
within our industry. Usually, it's typed out or something on some form, but there's always

00:16:23.739 --> 00:16:28.460
some going to be some handwritten forms and stuff. And so being able to extract that information,

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:34.700
and, and, you know, leverage, you know, handwritten, handwriting recognition,

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:41.979
for obtaining that data, that text, and putting it into a structured format,

00:16:41.979 --> 00:16:48.619
and that's always going to be a common application that is going to be needed in the insurance

00:16:48.619 --> 00:16:54.059
industry. Although I think now that there's, there's so much of that available, like, in any,

00:16:54.059 --> 00:16:58.460
you know, industry, that you can just buy something off the shelf, and you don't have to have a data

00:16:58.460 --> 00:17:05.739
science team dedicated to solving that problem. Same thing with like images. And if you're looking

00:17:05.739 --> 00:17:11.739
at, you know, trying to process claims much more quickly and efficiently, right, like if you take

00:17:11.739 --> 00:17:17.979
pictures of your car, because you got into a car accident, you want to estimate the damage of that

00:17:17.979 --> 00:17:22.619
claim, you know, sooner than later, right? You don't have to send a field agent out to

00:17:22.619 --> 00:17:28.619
inspect the car and look at it, you can just take pictures. So that's something that could also be

00:17:28.619 --> 00:17:32.780
done. I don't know anyone that's, I mean, I'm sure there are people that are looking at doing that.

00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:37.979
I don't know if there's companies that are doing that in production, and like you have customers

00:17:37.979 --> 00:17:43.660
sending in their claims that way. I haven't had a car accident in a while. But, you know, that's

00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:50.859
something that I can see being done as well. Have you thought of the NLP in the team? I don't know

00:17:50.859 --> 00:17:57.500
if you have any models running on the NLPs for the, as you mentioned about text analytics or

00:17:57.500 --> 00:18:06.459
understanding the claims and so on. Is there, what type of model that are right now in production,

00:18:06.459 --> 00:18:16.380
specifically built by your team? Is that focused on NLP and internet, some kind of

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:21.660
computer vision involved on it? Yeah, so we haven't done anything related to computer vision,

00:18:21.660 --> 00:18:28.459
but we have done projects related to NLP. So we've used spaCy, for example, to extract,

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:37.660
you know, more meaningful information from bodies of text to make, you know,

00:18:38.540 --> 00:18:47.339
more efficient decisions. But I wouldn't say it's like, it's not deep learning,

00:18:47.339 --> 00:18:52.380
it's still within that machine learning space. Yeah. Okay. Yep. Thanks.

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:57.579
Thanks, Darren. Thanks for the questions, too. Just a reminder, if anyone wants to ask anything

00:18:57.579 --> 00:19:02.540
anonymously, too, you can put it through on Slido, or just raise your hand and jump in.

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:10.780
But I wanted to ask you, Darren, when you were mentioning APIs and using APIs in production,

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:17.339
would you be able to share a bit more about what that looks like? And what? Yeah, so I think one

00:19:17.660 --> 00:19:25.020
Yeah, so I think one of the common problems that the businesses that we work with,

00:19:26.219 --> 00:19:36.060
from an underwriting function, is knowing if you have, you know, 30 applications to go through,

00:19:36.060 --> 00:19:40.780
you know, these are insurance applications. And as an underwriter, you have to make decision about

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:46.060
which ones to go through. And if you only have, you know, time to go through 10 of them,

00:19:46.859 --> 00:19:55.180
how are you going to prioritize that? So we have built an API that predicts the likelihood of,

00:19:55.180 --> 00:20:02.540
you know, that submission winning with our company. And so we'll give a grade out for that

00:20:02.540 --> 00:20:10.380
submission. And so if you have like a list of 30 submissions, each one has a grade, so A, B, C, D,

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:17.660
F, or whatever. And that way, the underwriter can, you know, order those rank from A's to B's

00:20:17.660 --> 00:20:27.339
and focus on those first. And so our API basically takes data, you know, the core, you know, data

00:20:27.339 --> 00:20:33.900
inputs of that submission feeds it into our server. And then we send a response back with

00:20:33.900 --> 00:20:39.339
that predicted grade. So that's kind of like a common example that we like to use when we're

00:20:39.339 --> 00:20:45.260
talking about APIs and how we use that within our team. That's great. Thank you.

00:20:46.859 --> 00:20:52.459
I see there's a question that just came through on Slido. And it was, do you think that insurance

00:20:52.459 --> 00:20:57.579
companies are underrated or misunderstood regarding how innovative they are?

00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:06.140
I think so. Yeah. When I joined this company two years ago, you know, I was just looking

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:12.060
for a new opportunity and I was working with a recruiter and he told me about this position.

00:21:12.060 --> 00:21:18.540
I was like, oh, insurance, like that sounds kind of boring. And all I knew about insurance at the

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:23.500
time was that I was paying for it and it's costing me a lot of money. And I really understand the

00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:29.660
need and the business need of insurance and how it works. And also how wide ranging insurance is

00:21:29.660 --> 00:21:34.540
when you think about it, like everything in business needs insurance, right? Because the

00:21:34.540 --> 00:21:39.420
business wants to minimize the risk and, you know, hand it off to somebody else by paying

00:21:39.420 --> 00:21:47.739
small amounts, you know, on a monthly or annual basis. So at the opportunities that I think

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:55.420
we have on our team are so significant because our company touches a wide range of products.

00:21:55.420 --> 00:22:01.099
You know, when you think of insurance, it's like auto health, home insurance, you know,

00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:09.420
just standard stuff. But there's insurance products for liability for dentists or lawyers,

00:22:10.459 --> 00:22:14.939
bookstores have their own special insurance, right? Even when you're looking at professional

00:22:14.939 --> 00:22:19.979
liability insurance, there's different liability insurance for different professions and how you

